Given a xhtml-macro that returns xhtml such as 

 

```

<ul>....</ul>

```

 

and regardless of the OutputType (BLOCK/INLINE), confluence will always render a paragraph before the HTML block element, regardless of its rendering mode being overridden by CSS, e.g. display: block or display: inline[-block].

 

What I would expect from confluence is that it does not make any such assumptions and render the markup as it was provided, e.g.

 
{noformat}
Something inline <ul><li>first item</li></ul> {noformat}
 

But instead, confluence renders this as

 
{noformat}
<p>Something inline&nbsp;</p>
<ul>...</ul> {noformat}
 

The rationale being here that the user agent is perfectly capable of rendering a display:block and display:inline[-block], without confluence making any "premature optimisations" or "assumptions" on its behalf.

 

In order to overcome this "bug", the macro then has to render the inline version as

 
{noformat}
<span><span>first item</span></span>{noformat}

which will then be rendered as one would expect. However, this will change the semantics and IMO we do not want that.

